column31: Stanford University enlists Kashmiri among top 2 percent scientists in world Available to contribute towards improving quality education in J&K: Dr M Iqbal Khan Jahangeer Ganaie Srinagar, Dec 24: A scientist from Srinagar presently working as Professor in the Department of Civil engineering at King Saud University has brought laurels to Kashmir as he has earned a very rare honour of figuring in top 2 per cent scientists in the world. Professor Mohammad Iqbal Khan a resident of Khan Mohalla, Chanapora, Srinagar an alumnus of NIT Srinagar and IIT Delhi who has earned his PhD degree in Structural Engineering from the University of Sheffield United Kingdom has been listed among two per cent scientists by Stanford University, one of the world's most prestigious Institutions based on the international evaluation of their research work. Dr Khan is faculty of University of Nottingham, UK, currently, working as Professor in the Department of Civil Engineering at King Saud University. He is an Adjunct Professor, at Department of Civil, Architecture and Environmental Engineering, Missouri University of Science and Technology, Rolla, USA and enrolled as visiting Professor at numerous universities in Canada, China and Germany. Concurrently, Prof. Khan currently holds many key positions in vital state-run R&D establishments viz. Managing Director, Center of Excellence for Concrete Research and Testing (CoE-CRT); Director, Laboratories of Structural Engineering Division in the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia. Prof. Khan is actively engaged in research in structural engineering and construction materials. His primary research interests are developing blast and impact-resistant materials; structural behaviour of concrete-filled tubes; nano- and micro-mechanics of composite materials; fibre-reinforced composites; sustainability and environmental impact; prediction modelling; and application of artificial intelligence. MANHATTAN ACC ADOPTABLE

Bebe 105361

1Y | M | Stray | 10 lbs.

A volunteer writes: This strapping adolescent boy in a tuxedo will do anything to get your attention. First, it's a chorus of meows. Then, it's poking his paws through the bars, and when he finally captures your attention, he lays down on all fours with his head up high, as if to say, see, see, look at how well-behaved I am. When I started petting him, he was finally calm; he craves abundant human contact. When a staff member visited Bebe, he climbed into her lap and was easy to pick up and return to his kennel. If you are looking for a love like no other, look no further, but look for him as soon as you can; he's as eager as can be.

KNOWN HISTORY:

Bebe was brought in as a stray, there is not information on his behavior in a home environment.

ENRICHMENT NOTES:

10/18/20
Lying flat at the back of the kennel. Becomes alert on approach but remains in place. Returns some soft blinks but remains very alert throughout the interaction. Not interested in treats or toys but tolerates touch. Has potential with some time. Gave shor-line cover.

10/22/20
Stress meowing and rolling around for attention. Wants to get out of the kennel. Seems as if he is trying to mate. Gave tuna, toys, stuffed toy, a box and a kuranda bed. Seems bored in kennel.

Social

Level 2

BEHAVIOR SUMMARY:

Bebe was at the front, standing tall, alert and curious, and allowed all petting and quickly pushed out to stand and lay on the assessor's lap while watching the nearby cats which caused her to low growl. She was easily picked up and placed back inside the kennel where he remained curious about life outside the kennel. He continued to enjoy all petting with a high tail and when offered catnip rolled in it, and began stretching and rolling on his back left and right. He became even friendlier on the catnip. He has a single bite incident that is not well explained but it's possible he may be prone to over-stimulating and some care should be exercised as he transitions into his new home.

Level 1
Dogs with Level 1 determinations are suitable for the majority of homes.

Level 2
Dogs with Level 2 determinations will be suitable for adopters with some previous dog experience.

Level 4

column31: Attorney General Merrick Garland announced Tuesday that the FBI and U.S. attorneys will work with state and local law enforcement to investigate "a disturbing spike in harassment, intimidation, and threats of violence against school board members, teachers and workers in our nationâ€™s public schools." With students returning to classrooms this fall, school board meetings have gone viral across the country as parents debate COVID-19 mask mandates and whether critical race theory (CRT) is included in curriculum. Garland's announcement did not mention a specific topic that the alleged threats were stemming from. Right-rated outlets and voices have paid much more attention to the issue than left- and center-rated sources. Many right-rated voices spoke out against the announcement, calling it a federal overreach with little justification. Some accused the Biden administration of trying to silence dissent from parents who oppose mask mandates and don't want CRT being taught to their children. At least one left-rated voice criticized Republican lawmakers who opposed Garland's decision, accusing them of siding with the "rising tide of angry threats" against school officials and seizing a chance "to portray themselves as the courageous and oppressed." Compare views in Washington Post, Reason and City Journal: https://www.allsides.com/story/perspectives-fbi-doj-probe-threats-against-school-officials

Level 1
Dogs with Level 1 determinations are suitable for the majority of homes.

Level 2

Level 4
Dogs with Level 4 determinations will need to go to homes with experienced adopters. The behavior challenges seen at Level 4 are seen at a much greater frequency and higher intensity than the other dogs in our care.

Subjective: BARH, no coughing/sneezing/vomiting/diarrhea

-Stage I dental disease

Good

-Start trazodone 7.5 mg/kg PO q12h indefinitely
-Recommend weight loss, monitor for worsening signs of allergies with placement

Surgery:
Neutered

TO ADOPT DIRECTLY FROM THE SHELTER - email adopt@nycacc.org. Put the dog's animal ID number on the subject line, and you must leave them your contact information.

Dogs with NH ONLY rating cannot be adopted directly from the ACC, so please message our page for assistance .

TO ADOPT or FOSTER: If you cannot get to the shelter in person to adopt, or want to foster, please message our page (Must Love Dogs - Saving NYC) www.facebook.com/mldsavingnycdogs)
OR email mld1nycdogs@gmail.com for guidance and assistance.

PLEASE NOTE: To foster, you have to be within prescribed range of NYC ACC approved New Hope rescues you are applying with,
and to adopt you will have to be in the general NE US area; NY, NJ, CT, PA, DC, MD, DE, NH, RI, MA, VT & ME (some rescues will transport to VA).

Shelter contact information:
Phone number: 212-788-4000 (automated only)
Email: adopt@nycacc.org

Manhattan Animal Care Center
326 East 110th Street
New York, NY 10029

Brooklyn Animal Care Center
2336 Linden Boulevard
Brooklyn, NY 11208

Staten Island Animal Care Center
3139 Veterans Road West
Staten Island, NY 10309

Adoption hours:
Monday through Friday: 12.00pm to 8.00pm
Saturday and Sunday: 10.00am to 6.00pm
(Closed on all Holidays and Training Days, as listed on their website www.nycacc.org)

Adoption fees depend on dog's age. Please email the ACC for more info. Fees include pre-adoption medical care and vaccines, deworming,
spay/neutering and one free follow-up visit to specific veterinarians.
---------------------------------
* NYC ACC RATING SYSTEM *

Level 1
Dogs with Level 1 determinations are suitable for the majority of homes.
Level 2

Dogs with Level 2 determinations will be suitable for adopters with some previous dog experience.
Level 3

Dogs with Level 3 determinations will need to go to homes with experienced adopters.

Level 4
Dogs with Level 4 determinations will need to go to homes with experienced adopters. The behavior challenges seen at Level 4 are seen at a much greater frequency and higher intensity than the other dogs in our care.

A Virginia judge ruled on Monday that a male student at Loudoun Countyâ€™s Stone Bridge High School is guilty of sexually assaulting a female student in a girlsâ€™ bathroom in May.

While gender fluidity was not raised during the hearing, court documents confirm the male suspect was wearing a skirt when the assault took place, reports Yahoo! News, adding that the female victim testified in court that she was violently coerced into performing sexual acts.

The male student, a 14-year-old boy, was later arrested in connection to the case on two counts of forcible sodomy, the Loudoun County Sheriffâ€™s Office said, according to a report by WUSA9.

The teen suspect was found guilty on all charges, reports WJLA 7News I-Team. Sentencing for the student will happen in November, but only after a Loudon County Judge determines the outcome of the second set of charges against the same student involving sexual battery at Broad Run High School.

After the assault at Stone Bridge High School, the male student was transferred to Broad Run, where he allegedly assaulted a second female student in early October.

The victimâ€™s family attorney, Bill Stanley of The Stanley Law Group, released a statement on behalf of the family on Monday, stating, â€œWe are relieved that justice was served today for the Smithâ€™s daughter.â€

â€œThis horrible incident has deeply affected the Smith family, and they are grateful for todayâ€™s outcome,â€ the statement added.

Around the time of the sexual assault in the girlsâ€™ bathroom, the Loudoun County School Board was concerning itself with a policy that would give students who believe they are the opposite sex access to school facilities, groups, and sports teams of their biological counterparts.

In June, Scott Smith, the father of the victim, went to a Loudoun County school board meeting looking for answers after his daughter was assaulted. A heated exchange ensued at the meeting, and Smith was arrested for obstruction of justice and disorderly conduct.

Hundreds of parents were also present to voice their concerns about the districtâ€™s transgender policy and Critical Race Theory (CRT). The school board eventually voted 7-2 to approve the transgender-related policy.

Earlier this month, Scott Ziegler, the superintendent of the embattled Loudoun County Public Schools, admitted that the school district â€œfailedâ€ to provide a safe environment for its students.

Zieglerâ€™s comments were in response to local parents outraged over how reports of the two sexual assaults were handled inside schools. Following the superintendentâ€™s statement, board member Beth Barts â€” who previously targeted parents who are against Critical Race Theory in schools â€” resigned from her position.

column31: This article explains why systemic racism and oppression remains in our schools. "There are six reasons or flaws that explain why schools have been unable to address disproportionate discipline referrals for students of color over the past 40 or more years. -Reason/Flaw #1. Educational leaders have tried to change the disproportionate numbers through policy and not practice. -Reason/Flaw #2. State Departments of Education (and other educational leaders) have promoted whole-school programs that are unproven or have critical scientific flaws. -Reason/Flaw #3. Districts and schools have implemented frameworks that target conceptual constructs, rather than instruction that teaches social, emotional, and behavioral skills. -Reason/Flaw #4. Districts and schools have not recognized that classroom management and teacher training, supervision, and evaluation are keys to decreasing disproportionality; and they are depending on Teacher Training Programs to equip their teachers with effective classroom management skills. -Reason/Flaw #5. Schools and staff have tried to motivate students to change their behavior when they have not learned, mastered, or are unable to apply the social, emotional, and behavioral skills needed to succeed. -Reason/Flaw #6. Districts, schools, and staff do not have the knowledge, skills, and resources needed to implement the multi-tiered (prevention, strategic intervention, intensive need/crisis management) social, emotional, and/or behavioral services, supports, and interventions needed by some students."

This handsome Prince needs an ortho consult for hind limb lameness :( A volunteer writes: Within a few minutes of meeting Prince, it was obvious I was in the presence of royalty! He is quick to do his â€œbusinessâ€ then it is straight to the serious task of getting attention!  He rubs himself against my legs like a cat letting me know heâ€™s ready for some pets.  His body turns into an accordion as I scratch up and down his spine seeming to squeeze his frame together then stretch like elastic in delight, smiling ear to ear while I play music on his back.  During our walk, I notice he has a funny, yet endearing gait to him, his back legs bowing out- possibly requiring some follow up medical care, but adorable nonetheless.

Look at Prince's expression of amazement in his photo. Is he envisioning a new home? He surely is heartbroken over losing his prior one, to which he did nothing wrong to deserve being discarded. He knows the value of a home, and truly cherished his. Prince's prior owner left him with impressive notes. Prince is very well behaved in a home, respectful, does well with dogs, and is still a puppy at heart with his toys. He wears a spicy pumpkin coat, and has a classically handsome face with fluttery ears. He is being faulted for reacting with sadness at being turned over to the shelter, obviously emotions aren't allowed. He arrived with lameness in a hind leg and had a cuticle removed, surely he feels this is the beginning of the end. His smile reveals a true heart and zest for life, therefore we know Prince is so deserving of a chance to live out the rest of his life.

For more information on adopting from the NYC AC&C, or to find a rescue to assist, please read the following: If you are local to NYC, and within 4 hrs of NYS and NJ and you are SERIOUS about adopting or fostering one of the animals at NYC ACC, please read our MUST READ section for instructions, or message our FB page with our experienced volunteers that will do their best to guide you through the process. * We highly discourage everyone from trusting strangers that send them Facebook messages, offering help, for it has ended in truly tragic events.* If you can get to the shelters in NYC: (212) 788-4000 (wait through the prompts to reach a live person) Email - adoption@nycacc.org http://www.nycacc.org/Adopt.htm https://www.facebook.com/NYCACC/ https://www.nycacc.org/about/locations If you are within a 3-4 hour radius of NYC or NJ and cannot get to the shelter: You must apply to a New Hope rescue shelter partner. Here's a list of New Hope shelter rescue partners (must contact individual rescues): https://www.nycacc.org/get-involved/new-hope/nhpartners For approved adopters, There is free transport within a 3-4 hour radius of NYC & NJ. column31: Street Traders Licence Update Some of you might know that I had an issue in July 2020 at Leamington Spa regarding the council requiring me to have a street traders licence. Iâ€™ve just been tagged into a post by Sharon Hargreaves on Canal Market Place who has just had a similar request from Chorley/Wigan council I have been quietly working on this issue so thought Iâ€™d better update you as to where weâ€™ve got to I went through the full council complaint procedure, which is lengthy, and then took it to the government ombudsman. They rejected my complaint on the grounds that the council had been operating lawfully, the laws they are referring to are: Local Government (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1982 and The Highway Act 1980 So at this point Iâ€™d reached a dead end, until Nevil Ingram contacted me, he sometimes trades with his stall The Big Cheese alongside the trading boats Sweet Barge and Shineonthewater, and is also a small business consultant. Nevil has consulted a City and a County Council, which are on the K & A stated they would not consider enforcing street trading licences, although another unitary authority on the K & A has tried to do so several years ago. The County Council has commissioned a legal opinion on canal trading which tells them that the traders on the towpath should not need street traders licences and that is their policy. So there are different approaches in different places and confusion about what the laws taken as a whole actually say. We feel that there is a need for protection for traders from licencing officers who are acting in this way. We have consulted with a licencing solicitor in Manchester and a barrister experienced in licencing that he works closely with. We have had a zoom meeting together, currently all for free on the basis of Nevilâ€™s friendship and connections, so weâ€™ve had an hour of free advice from a barrister and solicitor, this is what we discussed: Unfortunately, we have been advised/concluded that it is lawful/not unlawful for a licencing officer to require a boat to have street trader licence, although it is manifestly unreasonable â€“ we would say preposterous to consider a towpath a street, and that we have a good case given that we pay a trading levy to CRT and there is trading history on the canals We are proposing two approaches here â€“ short term and long term. Short term is to get a legal opinion written by both a licencing solicitor and a barrister to show how requiring a street traders licence is not backed up in law, which could be shown to any licencing officer who tries this. We believe that in most instances that would stop zealous licencing officers, who would need to go back and consult their in house solicitors, who would see the conflicts in the laws. We are progressing towards that and need to consult with a couple more organisations before publicising the issue and moving to a fund raiser to pay for that work . We are looking at a strategy of the trader refusing to stop trading and forcing the council to take them to court, and then vigorously defending the right to trade. In the longer term we aim to get the law changed to specifically exclude canal traders from needing a street traders licence. We want to move this forward in a collaborative and united way, constructive feedback welcomed We should be in a position to publicise more concrete information within a few days and will keep you all up to date.

1/28/20

 Lucas was placed with Vivian's House Dog Rescue. Please honor your pledges PayPal.me/vivianshousenj

 
Lucas just wants to be a good boy, his fear is just overwhelming him!
 
Just reading the notes it is clear that Lucas is completely terrified at the shelter.  He is not a bad dog, the notes do not say he is reacting with any aggression.  He is frozen in fear.  Just read - Lucas is very tense. When any attempt is made to touch him, he freezes. 1/16: Lucas is fearful of handlers and does not allow handling or collaring. He is introduced to the helper dog on a slip lead and appears soft, friendly, and interested.  So please help this guy get out of the shelter, into a home again, where he can relax and learn to be part of a family again.  Help Lucas find love again!

About 2 yrs old

In the assessment room, Lucas is very tense. When any attempt is made to touch him, he freezes. For this reason and out of concern for his stress levels, he is not a good candidate for a handling assessment at this time.

1/16: Lucas is fearful of handlers and does not allow handling or collaring. He is introduced to the helper dog on a slip lead and appears soft, friendly, and interested.

Summary: Growling at the other dog from the home

MEDICAL BEHAVIOR: Date of initial: 16-Jan-2020

ENERGY LEVEL:
We have no history on Lucas so we cannot be certain of his behavior in a home environment. However, he is a young dog who will need daily mental and physical activity to keep him engaged and exercised. We recommend long-lasting chews, food puzzles, and hide-and-seek games, in additional to physical exercise, to positively direct his energy and enthusiasm.

Behavior Asilomar TM - Treatable-Manageable

No children (under 13)

Place with a New Hope partner
Recommendations comments:

No children: Due to how uncomfortable Lucas is currently with touch and novel stimuli, we feel that an adult-only home would be most beneficial at this time.

Place with a New Hope partner: Lucas has not acclimated well to the kennel environment and is uncomfortable with touch, freezing when touched. We recommend placement with a New Hope partner who can provide any necessary behavior modification (force-free, positive reinforcement-based) and re-evaluate behavior in a stable home environment before placement into a permanent home.

Potential challenges:

Handling/touch sensitivity
Fearful

Handling/touch sensitivity: Lucas is highly uncomfortable with touch at the care center, freezing when any handling is done. He will need a very slow approach and to have touch paired with good things. Please see handout on Handling Sensitivity.
Fearful: Lucas is highly fearful at the care center, darting away from things he passes by. He will need a slow approach and time to acclimate to unfamiliar surroundings. Please see handout on Decompression Period.

PLEASE CONSIDER SAVING THE LIFE of a NYC ACC Death Row cat with your immediate offer to adopt.

TO GET STARTED IMMEDIATELY SEND A PRIVATE MESSAGE TO THIS PAGE (click "Send Message" from our home page). We will respond asap. You will be directed to complete an app with a registered 501(c)3 New Hope Rescue Partner, who is approved to pull cats from the NYC ACC (shelter). We will immediately alert the rescue of your incoming app.

ABOUT TRANSPORT: In most cases there is FREE TRANSPORT to your area up to a 4 hr. radius outside of NYC, including all or part of NY, NJ, CT, PA, NH, VT, RI, MA, MD, DE & DC (see the transport map provided). More distant adopters can meet the transport van, (i.e. a NC or VA adopter could meet in MD or DC, or an OH adopter could meet in PA).

ABOUT KITTENS: Kittens under 8 wks old & 2 lbs in weight are NOT PUBLICLY ADOPTABLE, due to their fragility. They can only be pulled by a rescue for specially-trained pre-approved kitten foster homes in NY, NJ & CT. Kittens over 8 weeks and 2lbs should preferably go in PAIRS.

ABOUT PLEDGES: Pledges are directly paid to the 501(c)3 NEW HOPE RESCUE PARTNER that pulls the the cat. Pledges do not guarantee a cat's life will be spared but may help a rescue org decide if they can afford to pull the cat and cover his/her vet expenses.

ABOUT US : MLC is 100% volunteer run page. We can help facilitate a rescue, by connecting you with an approved RESCUE group. We are not affiliated with the NYC ACC.

> TRUMP51 - NATIONAL

***Have you lost your mind.....Mark Milley***
# **Chairman of the Joint Chiefs Mark Milley Compared Trump to Hitler, His Supporters to Brownshirts: New Book**

In the wake of the 2020 election, Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff General Mark Milley apparently feared President Trump would attempt a coup and compared President Donald Trump and his supporters to Adolf Hitler and Nazi brownshirts, according to a new book. 

Written by The Washington Post's Philip Rucker and Carol Leonnig, I Alone Can Fix It purports to shine new light on how General Milley and other military brass feared and prepared for a showdown with their commander in chief.  

General Milley "was so shaken that then-President Donald Trump and his allies might attempt a coup or take other dangerous or illegal measures after the November election that Milley and other top officials informally planned for different ways to stop Trump," according to excerpts of the book obtained by CNN.

Milley felt obligated to be "on guard" for a potential coup attempt after Election Day, and reportedly said "they may try, but they're not going to f**king succeed." 

"Milley told his staff that he believed Trump was stoking unrest," claims the book, "possibly in hopes of an excuse to invoke the Insurrection Act and call out the military."

"You can't do this without the military" the book says Milley told his deputies. "You can't do this without the CIA and the FBI" because "we're the guys with the guns."

The book also says Milley saw President Trump as "the classic authoritarian leader with nothing to lose," calling the situation "a Reichstag moment" and "gospel of the FÃ¼hrer." Milley viewed the pro-Trump Million MAGA March as "the modern American equivalent of 'brownshirts in the streets.'"

CNN's report quotes a Department of Defense staffer close to Milley as responding to the forthcoming book's claims by saying Milley "tried his hardest to actively stay out of politics."

Donald Trump reacted to the book's claims about General Milley with a statement saying he "never threatened, or spoke about, to anyone, a coup of our government," calling the idea "so ridiculous." "If I was going to do a coup," Trump explained, "one of the last people I would want to do it with is General Mark Milley." 

"Never during my Administration did Milley display what he is showing now. He was not 'woke,'" Trump continued. "Actually I don't believe he ever was, but the way I look at Milley, he's just a better politician than a general, trying to curry favor with the Radical Left and the absolute crazy people espousing a philosophy which will destroy our country!"

As Townhall reported last month, General Milley made himself into a defender of the Left's divisive Critical Race Theory in a congressional hearing during which he said "I want to understand 'white rage,'" adding he finds it "offensive that we are accusing the United States military, our general officers, our commissioned, non-commissioned officers of being 'woke.'"

TO BE KILLED 06/28/2021

MAXIE THE LAP PUP <3 Maxie will capture your heart with his beautiful face and sweet disposition. A family pet through and through. Heartbreaking to learn he managed to break free from the transport crate in attempt to return to his loved ones. Upon arrival at the shelter Maxie was hesitant, naturally frightened and missing his family dearly while facing the unknown. You can see his worried expression and sad eyes in his photos. He has quickly opened up and showing the fun loving, friendly and affectionate youngster he is. During his assessment he was soft bodied, approached when summoned, and displayed no reactivity to people or dogs, accepted all handling, and agreeable to all assessment tasks. His prior home reported he can guard resources around the children, which reading between the lines means he was taunted the way children can and do play with pets. Maxie does not have a bite history, is young, healthy and oh so handsome! He was surrendered due to no fault of his own, and therefore deserves a forever home. He is a soft heart-ed boy always seeking attention, affection and praise. He is certainly a keeper! If you are interested in giving this solid sweetheart a chance through fostering or adopting, please message us. The shelter doesn't extend time to the doggies, including the awesome ones like Maxie.

A volunteer writes: This is one big sweet boy. He hung around me most of our time out in the backyard. Maxie likes to have the front half of his body on your lap (that's about 35 pounds), but who's complaining. He's a gentle soul and a bit of a big baby. Your heart will melt when he looks at you with those big brown eyes

ADOPTED! 

TO BE KILLED 04/30/2021

Meet Mika, young, lovable and the life of the party! If you have a soft spot for big, sincere yet tender eyes, you'll love this brown eyed girl. She comes complete with memorable bunny ears, an open and honest smile and a heart of gold. Mika is super enthusiastic and fun loving. She adores people and knows the secret to life is to enjoy it to the fullest. She has so much potential. It is clear she wants to be a part of a home and aims to please. While there is no background information on her, her time at the shelter has proven she is seeking a forever home, interested in learning the ropes and has an infectiously happy spirit. If you would like to give this delightful doll a chance, please message our page with inquiries.

column36:
As Americans celebrate our flag today, I am inspired by President Woodrow Wilson proclaiming the first Flag Day in 1916, as a way of uniting Americans. 

I am also inspired by two teachers. Dr. Bernard J. Cigrand who on June 14, 1885 put the American Flag on his desk and had his students write an essay in observance of â€˜Flag Birthdayâ€™. Four years later, a New York City kindergarten teacher, George Balch, planned Flag ceremonies in his school. This led to â€˜Flag Dayâ€™ being observed by the New York State Board of Education. 

Our flag must always remain a symbol of what unites Americans of all backgrounds. We must not let the forces at work in our schools, including right here in Westchester, divide us by indoctrinating our next generation of children by teaching them the destructive and divisive Critical Race Theory. 

This indoctrination sadly seeks to deprive us all of the promise of our shared American values, liberties and freedoms - all of which are endowed by God and not by government. 

Letâ€™s all recommit, especially those who run our institutions of learning and those who have taken up the vocation of teaching, to teach our kids to love our flag, to teach our kids to love our nation and to teach our kids to love all of our fellow Americans. Then we can truly safeguard all future generations so America lives up to the promise of our ideals and remains a beacon of hope for all; symbolized by our magnificent American Flag!

column34: At Manhattan ACC waiting for LOVE Simba Woof ID#123557, 2 years old, 67 lbs Handsome Simba is fearful at the shelter Needs a loving and experienced hero ASAP -Neutered
column35: Must Love Dogs - Saving NYC Dogs
column36:
KILLED 09/01/2021

TO BE KILLED 

**$250 DONATION**

A private donor has graciously offered to pay $250 to the New Hope partner that pulls Simba 123557. The shelter does not assume any responsibility for payment, nor does it warranty payment by this donor or any donor to you.

Lived in a crate for most of his life, 2 year old Simba is completely at a loss as to what life is all about.  His rescuer then dumped him quickly at a police station where because of an incident, the ACC is portraying him like a bad dog.  He is a scared pup at the ACC, and we can conclude that he was also freaked out at the precinct.  He refused the food offered to him, so the officer took the food and walked away, then Simba bit the policemanâ€™s pant leg.  The temp adopter said thereâ€™s no resource guarding seen in Simba, so what is it?  Scared animals think that humans are out to hurt or do something bad to them.  Imagine an injured cat , how angry and suspicious  he must be, and to approach him is foolish.  Dogs behave the same way when they are badly scared, they are on guard to defend themselves. Thatâ€™s nature. Simba thought the policeman was a threat, he was suspicious and scared, didnâ€™t accept the food, and lashed out when he thought he had the opportunity.  The notes said no provocation, which we humbly say there probably was, but might be perceptible only to the experienced dog person. The crucial point is Simba has not had good experiences with humans.  His adopter said he is a happy excitable puppy, which no one has seen up to this point.  This young boy has not had a life of comfort. In fact his life from the beginning, living in a crate, then 1 week of happiness at home with his adopter,  then betrayal by this very person.  Dumped at the police station and then dumped at the ACC.  From the four small walls of his crate, Simba most probably never imagined that his brief taste of freedom and â€œloveâ€ would end this way.  Dogs like Simba need our compassion and understanding, he needs us to help him find the miracle that he needs to get out alive.  We ask you, please help however you can, help this poor puppy who is most likely just over a year old.  He needs a committed experienced home with no children, because he is so scared at the ACC.   Please help Simba  have the life he deserves. 

Simba is fearful & needs an experienced, caring owner and home ASAP.

column31: So for tonightâ€™s episode. The comments and super chats were just really annoying. I wish there was a way to remove spam idiots. However, i felt it was fair and educational especially in how you get to see into the mind of the other side. It could honestly help you to figure out what to expect and how best to prepare to counter their narratives, but the first step is always being open and willing to have the discussion. Itâ€™s not about having an echo chamber like the partisans, itâ€™s about having a discussion. Thatâ€™s the only way to avoid the culture war fully exploding in my mind, and why it probably will explode. I feel tim wasnâ€™t prepared for the points that the guy brought up which left him at a disadvantage. 1. Covid deaths and trump was a huge fight but they shoulda brought up the deaths per million and such and woulda seen that the US is not the worst. Honestly Tim needed someone there to go look for the facts to help argue it. He also shoulda brought up the panic over toilet paper. Plus, the hindsight argument coulda been done better. The CDC and WHO kept flip flopping and nobody knew anything. And there is the need to keep up morale like any good leader knows. Also the stats for the death contributions of the Dem governors woulda come well. The list is extensive but Tim wasnâ€™t prepared to debate. 2. Healthcare honestly never gets looked at properly because socialized medicine is cool if you are looking to treat everyone but not for research and development of those treatments. Plus, Trump and the drug prices and fighting big Pharma woulda been a good point to hammer him with. 3. The schools showed the guy actually supporting school choice in theory but just hating on it cus of his TDS. Tim coulda caught him on that. 4. Critical race theory was just a mess cus the guy didnâ€™t even share the main idea of critical race theory to me. It seemed he had some utopian idea that honestly most of the left wouldnâ€™t agree with. 5. His labeling of the right and left coulda been handled better if Tim had hit hard against him on the Far Left and not let him get off with how the left is diverse but the right is all fascist.

column31: Introducing Tank. This adorable little guy is amazing! Tank was found as a stray out roaming the streets of Mesquite. Weighing in at 2.8 lbs, it is amazing that he survived out there. Luckily, he was turned into Mesquite Animal Shelter by a good Samaritan. When no owner stepped forward to claim him, the team at the Mesquite Animal Shelter reached out to CRT to see if we could bring him into our program and help him to find his forever home. We were happy to help him, Tank has stolen our hearts. Tank is a sweet, lean, cuddling machine. He enjoys other small dogs and has fit right into the pack, even though his foster mates are 2-3 times his size. Tank is not afraid to play with them at all. We are not sure he has looked in the mirror to see how small he is! He definitely holds his own and often is the instigator of play! So far, we have not really seen him playing with toys, but he is curious about them. Tank really loves his human family and wants to be near them all the time. He is super excited to be held, to play or cuddle with them. They have chosen to have him sleep overnight in a large crate because of his size & fear of injuring him in their sleep. Tank does, however, love a nice afternoon nap on the bed with them. Our vet estimates that Tank is about 2-3 years old. He seems to adapt to new situations quickly. Tank weighs about 2.8 pounds, and is slightly underweight. We have him on a high nutrition diet so he can safely gain a little weight. Our vet thinks he should be about 3.5 to 4 pounds at his ideal weight. He will always be a tiny dog. Ideally, we are looking for a family that is experienced with very small dogs for his forever home. Tank loves going outside and exploring the backyard. Note that Tank is small and therefore will always need his human nearby while he is out (there are instances where hawks or large birds will swoop down and pick up small dogs under 5 pounds, so you will want to be there to protect Tank). We also want to emphasize that your fence must be very secure. Tank is so tiny that she can easily slip under the smallest opening in a fence, so he will need to be in a home with a solid, fenced yard (preferably wooden fence). Note that he does like to explore and will definitely check out your fence area. Please be sure that your yard and home are very secure in all aspects. Tank has not been in foster care long, so he is not housebroken yet. He is very smart and will hopefully train easily. We are working with him daily and have already seen improvement in the time he has been with us. Tankâ€™s ideal home would be one with activity and lots of love to share. We think Tank would enjoy another small dog as a buddy, but we also think he would do fine as an only dog as long as his family was around a lot and gave him lots and lots of love. He would be great for a work at home or retired family where he could spend the afternoon on a warm lap. Tank is generally very quiet, but he will probably alert you if he hears someone coming! Due to his tiny size and small frame, he should not be in a home with children. This little guy is so sweet, and we are excited to help him find his forever home.! Tank is being fostered in the Dallas/Ft. Worth, Texas area. Our CRT adoption form can be found at: https://www.chihuahua-rescue.com/adoption-application/

FOUND TIED UP BY THE POLICE, precious young Leonidas felt the need to defend and protect himself when he was being examined. This beautiful chocolate boy with expressive eyes obviously didnâ€™t have a good start in his life. Bloody diarrhea, then abandoned tied up, Leonidasâ€™ people most probably had very little regard for him. Yet after being treated the way he was, and under all that fear, Leo has warmed up and has become highly social to staff members he has grown to like. Leonidas has a good heart, waiting for the right human to bring out the best in him. In spite of his initial lunging and barking, Leonidas earned a Level 3 rating because he has shown his good side. Please someone save this boy who just wants to make friends, if only he was given love and kindness early in his life. Itâ€™s not too late because Leonidas WANTS TO TRUST ! Please advocate for this poor boy whose life will end soon.

column36:
September 24, 2020 (Thursday)

Tonight, protesters in Louisville, Kentucky, Philadelphia, Baltimore, New York City, Rochester, and other cities are calling for justice and reminding observers that Black Lives Matter after a grand jury on Wednesday declined to charge the three officers involved in Breonna Taylorâ€™s murder. The grand jury did indict Brett Hankison, one of the officers involved, on charges of first-degree wanton endangerment for shooting into her apartment and that of her neighbors without a clear line of sight. His actions, according to the charge, exhibited â€œextreme indifference to the value of human life,â€ Hankison had to post a bond of $15,000. 

On March 13, three plainclothes Louisville police officers broke down the door of Breonna Taylorâ€™s apartment as part of an investigation of a man they believed was a drug dealer in a different part of the city. Taylor had once dated the man, and police say they believed he had used her apartment to receive packages. They broke in without announcing who they were, and when they came through the door, Taylorâ€™s boyfriend, who had a license to carry a gun, thought they were criminals and shot one of them in the leg. The three officers fired off 32 shots, six of which hit Taylor, a 26-year-old emergency room technician. 

She died within minutes.

The officers found no drugs.

After Taylorâ€™s death, the officers involved filled out an incident report that said they had not forced their way into the apartmentâ€”witnesses and crime scene photographs show they didâ€”and listed Taylorâ€™s injuries as â€œnone.â€ 

On September 15, Taylorâ€™s family and the city of Louisville announced they had reached a record-breaking $12 million settlement in the shooting, Louisvilleâ€™s largest ever for police actions and one of the largest in the nation for the shooting of a Black American by law enforcement officers. The settlement includes a wide range of police reforms. 

But when announcing the criminal charges, Kentucky Attorney General Daniel Cameron explained that Hankisonâ€™s bullets had not hit Taylor, so he could not be charged in her death. And since her boyfriend had shot at them first, the officers who did kill Taylor were justified in their use of force. It is unlikely there will be other charges, he said. The lawyer for Taylorâ€™s family has called the six-month investigation a cover-up, and has asked Cameron to release the transcripts of the grand jury proceedings.

Democratic Governor Andy Beshear agreed that "It's time to post all the informationâ€¦. All the facts, all the interviews, all the evidence, all the ballistics, to truly let people look at the informationâ€¦. One of the problems we've had over the last six months is a total lack of explanation and information," he added. "And the vacuum that's created there â€” our emotions, frustrations â€” can truly fill that. It's time for people ... to be able to come to their own conclusions about justice."

Cameron, a Republican, cited the pending trial and an FBI investigation as a reason to keep the evidence under wraps. â€œAt this point, I donâ€™t think itâ€™s appropriateâ€ to release more information, he said. 

â€œI have to say, as an attorney, that the decision didnâ€™t surprise me,â€ said Savala Trepczynski of the University of California Berkeley School of Law. â€œItâ€™s very hard to hold the police accountable in a deep way... given the system thatâ€™s in place and how it tends to favor police at every turn. As a person, though, the (decision) is upsetting, disappointing, angering â€” all of those things. I felt grief, a familiar grief.â€

The idea that our laws are written in such a way that they privilege white people and disadvantage people of color, especially Black Americans, is the principle at the heart of critical race theory. This is the theory that Trump has called â€œun-American propaganda,â€ and which he has ordered federal agencies to stop addressing. 

Trump learned about critical race theory from Tucker Carlsonâ€™s show on the Fox News Channel, and that show, too, was in the news today. A federal judge dismissed a lawsuit brought against Carlson by Karen McDougal, a former Playboy model who claims to have had an affair with Trump before he became president. In 2018, on his show, Carlson accused McDougal of extorting Trump. She sued him for defamation. 

Lawyer Erin Murphy argued for FNC that Judge Mary Kay Vyskocil, a Trump appointee, should toss the lawsuit because Carlsonâ€™s show is not news. It is commentary, Murphy said, and so he has no obligation to tell the truth. Murphy said that a reasonable viewer should recognize that Carlson simply provides hypothetical statements to offer â€œprovocative things that will help me think harder,â€ and his accusations against McDougal, couched as questions, were simply provocations. "What weâ€™re talking about here, itâ€™s not the front page of The New York Times," Murphy said. â€œItâ€™s Tucker Carlson (truncated)

I'd like to repost this great letter from a teacher in Iowa to a noisy little TV dinner heir in need of some tutoring 

Dear Tucker Carlson,

Hey Tuck, I just got done watching a segment of your show. You know, the one where you suggest that there should be a camera in every classroom in order to root outâ€¦let me get this accurateâ€¦â€civilization ending poison.â€ https://twitter.com/ndrew_lawrence/status/1412566208763895810

Iâ€™m going to zig where you thought most teachers would zag. I welcome your Orwellian cameras in my classroom. Frankly, I donâ€™t know many teachers who would object to having people watch what we do. As a matter of fact, I hate to tell you this Tucker Swanson McNear Carlson, but most of us spent the last year having video cameras in our classrooms.

See, I think you believe that your suggestion that people see what happens in our classrooms will somehow scare teachers. The truth of it is that we have been begging for years to have people, such as yourself, come into our classrooms. I somewhat famously asked Ms. DeVos to visit a public school before she became Secretary of Education (https://www.huffpost.com/entry/an-introduction-from-public-school-teachers-to-betsy_b_5845e2fbe4b0707e4c8171a3). Itâ€™s unclear whether she has yet to set foot in an actual public school classroom, but I digress. I sense that you think youâ€™ll see all of us pinko teachers speaking endlessly about Critical Race Theory leading toâ€¦and again, let me get this right, â€œcivilization ending poison.â€ Iâ€™ve been in a lot of classrooms (more than you I am willing to bet) and I think youâ€™re going to be disappointed on that front.

What happens in Americaâ€™s classrooms is teaching and learning. Your â€œspy camerasâ€ will see teachers and students working together to be better every day. Iâ€™ll tell you what I saw on a tour of classrooms not that long ago. I saw a group of kindergartners trying to create bridges over running water with basic classroom supplies in a lesson about collaboration. I saw a high school literature class talking about the character development in The Glass Menagerie. I saw a middle school history class participating in group project where they had to solve problems in a fictional city, with specifics of how they would utilize resources and build public support for their projects. Anyone watching your cameras will see learningâ€¦all day every day.

For those who watch your â€œnanny camsâ€ carefully, theyâ€™ll see a lot of other things as well. They will see teachers working with students who have vastly different life experiences. They will see students who are fluent in multiple languages working with teachers to become proficient in yet one more language. They will see students who are hungry get their one solid meal a day in the cafeteria. They will see students itching for more fine arts, industrial technology, or world languages to be offered in their school. In my classroom, if weâ€™re being honest, theyâ€™ll probably hear some sketchy intonation from my saxophones, and I promise weâ€™re working on it. But for sure, they will see learningâ€¦all day every day.

To be honest, Iâ€™m fascinated by the logistics of your proposal. In a world where school districts are struggling to recruit and maintain teachers, who is going to man your â€œcitizen review boardsâ€ (setting aside the fact that public school teachers already answer to publicly elected school boards)? For instance, in my school district I sense you would need well over 500 cameras going every day. Who watches those 500 screens 10 hours a day (I want you watching my 7 am jazz band and my after school lessons)? What qualifications would these â€œexpertsâ€ need to know what they were watching for? What happens when they catch a teacher teachingâ€¦let me get this rightâ€¦â€civilization ending poison?â€ Who do they report that to? Iâ€™m also curious who will pay for all of this incredible technology. Maybe I missed it, but can you point me to a K-12 institution where Critical Race Theory is being taught? Hell, can you define Critical Race Theory for all of us? Iâ€™m sure youâ€™ve got answers to all of these questions.

Frankly, Iâ€™ve never been able to figure out, instead of dreaming up Orwellian plans to have Big Brother in all of our classrooms, why you donâ€™t round up an army of bright young conservatives to actually step up and teach? Is it because teachers work hard, arenâ€™t paid as much as those with similar educational backgrounds, donâ€™t have support from our elected officials, constantly serve as punching bags for those who donâ€™t understand public education, or is it just because itâ€™s easier to throw rocks at a house than to build one?

Hereâ€™s the real deal Tuck, I grew up with my mom making me eat your familyâ€™s Salisbury Steaks once every couple of weeks (his family makes Swanson TV dinners) for many years. I struggle to take advice on teaching and learning from a guy who makes a steak that, on its best day, tastes like shoe leather that has been left out in a goat pasture (truncated)

column35: Nu Skool Presents:  Uprooting Cellular Anti-Blackness w/Dr. Kenjus Watson
column36:
Register Here: https://nu-skool-solidarity.eventbrite.com
Kenjus Watson, Ph.D. is a Postdoctoral Fellow in the Health and Equity Research Lab in the Biology Department at San Francisco State University. Uprooting Cellular Anti-Blackness will enlighten us on mind-blowing research that reveals adverse effects of toxic anti-black racism.  We are invited to reflect deeply on the bio-psycho-social impact of everyday racism, particularly in schooling spaces from kindergarten to college.  We will also engage and share practices that can foster cellular healing and restoration. His research concerns critical race theory, the biopsychosocial impact of everyday racism on Black students, the promises of school abolition and the re-Indigenization of Education.  Kenjus also teaches courses in the Education Department and Black Studies Program at Occidental College. He earned his BA in Psychology at Occidental College, and his Ph.D. in Education with an emphasis in Race and Ethnic Studies at UCLA. See more. Other resources: https://www.apocalypticeducation.org/

Hello, my name is Fortesque. My animal id is #88843. I am a male brown brindle dog at the Manhattan Animal Care Center. The shelter thinks I am about 3 years 1 weeks old.

I came into the shelter as a agency on 2/19/2020.

Sorry, this pet is for new hope partners only.

Fortesque is at risk for behavioral reasons. Fortesque came to us as a stray after being found tied to a park bench, so not much is known about his past. At the care center, Fortesque has remained fearful and has displayed distant behaviors such as barking and growling, particularly around people he doesn't know. Fortesque has not allowed for some extensive handling, but in time, does allow for leashing and will go out on a walk and is social but will growl and react to strangers. It is possible that in time, Fortesque will become more comfortable, but will need a gradual acclimation and slow introduction to new people and environments. He would be best suited for placement with a new hope partner that can provide the necessary behavior modification. Medically, Fortesque was diagnosed with canine infectious respiratory disease complex which is contagious to other animals and will need further care.

You may know me from such films as...
https://youtu.be/DIgEB4wXdpY

Let's get to know each other a bit more...
A staff member writes "Fortesque takes his time making new friends but once the key to his heart, food, is found, he will warm up quickly. He needs a special person who will understand that he has a guarded heart and will make friends at his own pace. A quiet home where he will have the space and time to do this would be ideal for him. Once he gets to know his people he will be a loyal friend."

UPDATE STORMY IS SAFE OUT THE BUILDING 5/30/20 

To know her is to love her! Only sunny skies with this sweet doll Stormy! She earned the prized level 1 behavior rating and is only too happy to demonstrate why. Stormy does everything with finesse and sincerity. Her honest to goodness heart cannot be beat. Both shelter staff and her prior owner agree upon her excellence. She does nicely with children, dogs and cats. She is well behaved when left alone, seeks attention and affection, soft bodied, shares all resources, allows all handling, and obedient. She lacks nothing except a loving home. She also happens to be easy on the eyes, though she is too pleasantly plump at the moment. If you are interested in this angel, please message our page. 

Super Sweet Level 1 Stormy needs follow-up care for possible hypothyroidism!

STORMY@BROOKLYN ACC
Stormy ID#94455, 8 years old, 80 lbs
Came into shelter as Owner Surrender 
MEDICAL BEHAVIOR EVALUATION:
BEHAVIOR RATING: Level 1

Medical:
Obese, Thinning of Fur / Tail (suspect hypothyroidism); a little nervous but did well for shaving and has started leaning into pets!

History: OS

P = WNL

MSI: Ambulatory x 4, skin free of parasites, no masses noted, dry/greasy/dull coat, generalized thinning of coat with a rat tail appreciated and mild truncal alopecia

Obese
Thinning of fur/rat tail r/o underlying endocrinopathy (hypothyroidism) vs underlying allergies vs other

Fair-Good

CTM while at BACC

Recommend further hypothyroid work-up (FT4 byED and TSH)and weight loss with placement

RBC 4.59 (N 5.65 - 8.87 M/ÂµL)

WNL

CBC-> Mild nonregenerative anemia

Profile: This behavior note was written by the previous owner of this pet. Animal Care Centers of NYC provides this as a guide for optimal pet placement.
Please use these notes in conjunction with the information provided by NYCACC.
 
Animal ID: 94455
Animal Name: Stormy
Breed: Large Mixed Breed
This animal came from: Found Stray
Origin Address 
Spay/Neuter Status: Spayed

Basic Information: Stormy is an 8 year old altered female large mixed breed who was surrendered into BACC due grandson having allergies as well as moving and no pets are allowed. There are no known injuries. However, she appears to have dermatitis.

Previously lived with: 2 adults 1 child

How is this dog around strangers? Client stated that Stormy is shy for a few minutes around strangers.

How is this dog around children? Client stated that Stormy is relaxed, affectionate and usually tolerant around her grandson.

How is this dog around other dogs? Client stated that Stormy is relaxed, playful, and respectful around the other family dogs.

How is this dog around cats? Client stated that Stormy is relaxed and respectful around cats.

Resource guarding: none

Bite history: none

Housetrained: Yes

Energy level/descriptors: medium

Other Notes: Client stated that Stormy has overall good behavior and is not bothered during storms or fireworks. Client stated that Stormy is not bothered when touching her bowl or food while eating, taking a teat or away, or being taken off the furniture. Client stated that Stormy is friendly when being held or restrained, disturbed while resting or sleeping, being bathe, or being brushed. Client stated that Stormy is not bothered when having her nails trimmed. Client stated when someone unfamiliar approaches the family or house, Stormy is afraid.

Has this dog ever had any medical issues? Yes

Medical Notes: Client stated that Stormy was last seen by the ASPCA on May 17. 2020 due to dermatitis.

For a New Family to Know: Client describes Stormy as friendly, affectionate, playful, and shy with a medium activity level. Client stated her favorite trait of Stormy is that Stormy is playful. Client stated that Stormy's favorite activity is playing with her rope. Client stated that when she is home, Stormy is in the same room as she is or will follow her around. Client stated that Stormy loves to play (truncated)

UNALTERED MALE, SMALL MIXED BREED
OWNER SURR FROM NY 
MEDICAL BEHAVIOR EVALUATION: 
BEHAVIOR RATING:

Pet whimpering in kennel.

Move to medical when space available.

DVM Intake Exam
Estimated age: About 9 years old
Microchip noted on Intake? Scanned engative
History: Owner surrender due to crying at night. Hx SARDS 6/2020. Since 9/2/20, pet has been on Galliprant 60 mg 1/2 tablet SID PO & Gabapentin 100 mg 2 caps TID PO for IVDD. Previous episode of IVDD in 5/2018 treated with codeine by local ER. Owner brought nystatin-neomycin-sulfate-thiostrepton-triamcinolone ointment which she has been placing around the eyes.
Subjective: QAR
Observed Behavior -

Evidence of Trauma seen - No
Objective
P = 130
R = 36
BCS 7/9
EENT: Cornea, clear moist OU, brown exudate at medial canthus OD. Fundus wnl OU. Ears clean, no nasal or ocular discharge noted

PLN: No enlargements noted
H/L: NR, NMA, CRT < 2, increased upper airway noise referred over cranial lung fields, eupneic
ABD: Non painful, no masses palpated
U/G: Male, intact. Two scrotal testicles.
MSI: 5 mm grey purple nodule at 2 o'clock around anus. Pain on downward palpation of lower back. Sensitivity when hips extended. Ambulatory x 4, skin free of parasites, healthy hair coat
CNS: Mentation appropriate. Negative menace but positive palpebral OU. No CP deficits. Peripheral reflexes WNL.
Rectal: WNL externally

Assessment
Blind r/o Sudden acquired retinal degeneration syndrome.
Recurrent back pain r/o IVDD vs neoplasia vs other
Overweight
Periodontal disease stage 3/4
Perianal mass r/o adenoma
Prognosis: Fair

Discontinue NSAID due to lack of efficacy
Hydromorphone 2mg/ml 0.7ml IM Caudal left thigh
Gapapentin 100mg 2 capsules PO BID
Trazodone 50mg 1.5 tablets po bid indefinitely
+/- amantadine 10mg/ml 5mls sid, start steroid trial after 3 to 5 day washout period
Advise placement asap for pain control, cage rest +/- MRI

SURGERY:
Temporary waiver due to chronic back pain.

TO ADOPT DIRECTLY FROM THE SHELTER - email adopt@nycacc.org. Put the dog's animal ID number on the subject line, and you must leave them your contact information. 
Dogs with NH ONLY rating cannot be adopted directly from the ACC, so please message our page for assistance . 

TO ADOPT or FOSTER: If you cannot get to the shelter in person to adopt, or want to foster, please message our page (Must Love Dogs - Saving NYC) www.facebook.com/mldsavingnycdogs) 
OR email mld1nycdogs@gmail.com for guidance and assistance. 

PLEASE NOTE: To foster, you have to be within prescribed range of NYC ACC approved New Hope rescues you are applying with, 
and to adopt you will have to be in the general NE US area; NY, NJ, CT, PA, DC, MD, DE, NH, RI, MA, VT & ME (some rescues will transport to VA). 

Shelter contact information:
Phone number: 212-788-4000 (automated only)
Email: adopt@nycacc.org 

Manhattan Animal Care Center
326 East 110th Street
New York, NY 10029

Brooklyn Animal Care Center
2336 Linden Boulevard
Brooklyn, NY 11208

Staten Island Animal Care Center
3139 Veterans Road West
Staten Island, NY 10309

Adoption hours: 
Monday through Friday: 12.00pm to 8.00pm
Saturday and Sunday: 10.00am to 6.00pm 
(Closed on all Holidays and Training Days, as listed on their website www.nycacc.org) 

Adoption fees depend on dog's age. Please email the ACC for more info. Fees include pre-adoption medical care and vaccines, deworming, 
spay/neutering and one free follow-up visit to specific veterinarians.

---------------------------------
* NYC ACC RATING SYSTEM *
Level 1
Dogs with Level 1 determinations are suitable for the majority of homes.

Level 2
Dogs with Level 2 determinations will be suitable for adopters with some previous dog experience.

Level 3
Dogs with Level 3 determinations will need to go to homes with experienced adopters.

column35: APPLIANCE, FREON, CRT & ELECTRONICS RECYCLING COLLECTION for the Woburn Council of Social Concern
column36:
The Medeiros Crew Recycling group will once again be holding appliance, Freon, CRT, and electronics recycling drives. 

The next event is on Saturday, September 18, 2021 from 9 to 1 at the Spence Farm property located at 41 Wyman Street in Woburn.  

For the health and safety of all, masks will be required to be worn by both customers and volunteers during the collection. Thank you!

This is an excellent opportunity to recycle these items at a minimal cost, while supporting a local group or organization each month. 

There is a significant cost savings compared to the higher cost associated with curbside appliance recycling programs.  

In Woburn, the cost for curbside pick-up of many of these items has increased once again in 2021.

The drop-off recycling drives at Spence Farm are open to residents and businesses from all communities, not just Woburn. 

With your support, over the years these collections have raised over $200,000 for local non-profit organizations, as well as several thousand dollars in donations to the Woburn Memorial High School Scholarship Fund.  

So, clean out those basements, attics, garages, and warehouses and bring your items to the next drive on Saturday, September 18th. 

Please be aware that if you cannot make this collection, the next one is not until October 16th here at the Spence farm building! 

Please see photo for pricing.

Should you have any questions, please contact Paul or Lori Medeiros at (781) 938-0297 or at paulderman@verizon.net

2/25/20 

Ghost has been placed with AmsterDog. Please honor your pledges. https://www.amsterdog.org/donate

JUST A 9 MONTH OLD PUPPY!  SCARED AND ALONE AND NOW AT RISK!

Shy, at first, with people, Ghost then becomes affectionate and friendly once he knows you.  He plays well with other dogs, but feels so lost and scared at the shelter.  THIS IS A GOOD SWEET BOY!  Owner described Ghost as being friendly, affectionate and shy.  He likes to play with balls, and squeaky toys and  fetch, tug, and chase are his favorite ways to spend time.. His favorite treats are bone chew treats. Ghost is just an innocent puppy that has only known the world of his family.  He needs a hero to show him that everything will be ok, that there is happiness to be had and a life to live. So please help Ghost find this!  Please help #SAVEGHOST now!

Ghost is otherwise healthy.

ABD: Tense, non-painful, no masses palpated U/G: MI, 2 palpable testicles, no discharge MSI: Ambulatory x 4, skin free of parasites, no masses noted, healthy hair coat CNS: Mentation appropriate - no signs of neurologic abnormalities Rectal: Not performed, externally normal Assessment: Otitis externa Prognosis: Good Plan: CTM while at BACC Start trazodone 7.5mg/kg PO BID indefinitely for FAS Neuter. Recommend routine ear cleanings and treatment of otitis with placement. Surgery: Okay for surgery BEHAVIOR DETERMINATION: New Hope Only Recommendations: No children No cats Place with a New Hope partner Recommendations comments: No children: Due to Smores' history with children in his previous home, we recommend an adult only home. Place with a New Hope partner: Due to Smores' history in his previous home, we recommend placement with a New Hope partner who can re-evaluate his behavior in a stable home environment before placement into a permanent home. No cats: Due to Smores' intolerance of cats, he should be placed in a cat-free environment. ******* TO FOSTER or ADOPT ******* ************************************** ğŸ“ PLEASE Private Message Dogs Lives Matter - Saving NYC Dogs or email us at NYCDogsLivesMatter@gmail.com if you can FOSTER or ADOPT ğŸ“ ************************************** To foster, you have to be within prescribed range of NYC ACC approved New Hope rescues you are applying with, & to adopt you will have to be in the general NE US area; NY, NJ, CT, PA, DC, MD, DE, NH, RI, MA, VT & ME (some rescues will transport to VA). ************************************** RE ACC site: Just because a dog is not on the ACC site does NOT necessarily mean safe. There are many reasons for this like a hold or a behavior evaluation has not been conducted yet or the dog is rescue-only... the list goes on... Please, do share these pups as well until their threads are updated with their most current status. Thank you for caring! â™¥ ************************************** This flyer was created with care by Dogs Lives Matter - Saving NYC Dogs NYCDogsLivesMatter@gmail.com...

Bloom is on the emergency placement list due to behavioral reasons. Bloom has deteriorated in the care center, refusing to walk when out of her kennel and constant barking and panting while in the kennel. Medically, Bloom is a little underweight but otherwise healthy.

She refused to walk when out of the kennel. In the kennel, she is constantly barking and panting and no longer engages with enrichment. Bloom would do best in an experienced, adult-only, single-pet home that would allow her the time and space to decompress.

Prince lived with 2 children between the ages of 10 and adulthood. He is relaxed and affectionate with children and plays gently with them.

Prince was an indoor and outdoor cat who would sometimes spend time with other cats. His owner reported that there were some outdoor cats he would play gently with and at other times he would return home with scratches and other wounds. His owner did not know the sexes of the outdoor cats.

high

Prince has never been given a bath, had his nails trimmed or his coat brushed. Prince enjoys being picked up and held. He is afraid when he is put into a carrier. Prince does not have any favorite toys. Prince's previous owner stated that he is an indoors-outdoors cat who who had the choice to spend his time either outside or indoors; he tends to spend his nights inside the home. Prince likes to sleep on a chair or the rug. Prince eats both wet and dry food from the Meow brand in an unknown amount and frequency. Prince's favorite treats are beef, chicken and salmon. Prince uses the bathroom both inside and outside, he uses an uncovered litterbox inside the home which is filled with clumping litter. SAFE !  Pulled by rescue ! 

TO BE KILLED: APR. 27, 2021

Sweet Senior Meredith is very social with handlers but will require a only pet home can you help!? ğŸ™‚ The queen of the belly rubs! Age may just be a number, but a golden heart is forever! Meredith is our 10 year old princess deserving a loving home before the shelter decides her fate. Her frosted face and huge brown eyes have much experience, as do the telltale signs of being a momma at some point in time. Who would expect her to shake and wiggle with excitement like the youngsters do? She seems to forget her age in the presence of treats. Her video shows how filled to the brim with life she is, as well as how lovable she is to people. Her aversion to other dogs is why the shelter decided she doesn't deserve a fair chance to find an adopter or foster. After becoming acquainted with her and viewing her video, the evidence is very clear, she is a joyful doggie who will bring much happiness into a home. What are the chances of a fun loving, affectionate, spry senior finding love when there are so many younger souls begging at the shelter? Surely her desire to connect with people, her excitement over treats and her ability to shake, rattle and roll might set her apart. Don't forget about those belly rubs!  Sadly her time is numbered. The only walk we want to see her take is her freedom walk. If you can foster or adopt this uniquely deserving senior, please message our page now!

She has appeared friendly and social when one-on-one with human handlers, though may quickly become overly aroused upon hearing other dogs in the shelter, even when out of sight. She leans into petting, is solicitous with handlers, and has been very treat-motivated. Meredith would succeed best outside of a shelter or boarding environment, and should be kept out of areas with high levels of dog traffic. It is recommended that Meredith be conditioned to wearing a basket muzzle in instances where she may encounter other animals outdoors. She requires an adult-only, single pet home.

column35: This is a re-share of a post
column36:
I posted a question to all school committee members and candidates last week. The question was direct and simple. Are you in favor of teaching cert in the Fall River School System?

As of this date, I have only received one response. I should say I did not tag anyone only because I know many candidates in all the races read my page or watch my show because when they don't like something they comment. Having said that Shelly Pereira did comment and I will post it below. First let me just say this, thank you for answering my question and I very much appreciate it. I also appreciate how you articulate your view. I believe that is critical. I believe what else is critical is the fact that people learn and understand what critical race Theory actually is. I think that is really confusing to most. However, I will say as a substance use disorder counselor for over 25 years I took numerous trainings and coursework in different forms of cultural diversity. One in particular was understanding Multicultural diversity. I believe was the best I ever took covering almost every call Drew we encounter. Critical race Theory unfortunately does teach that people are judged by the color of their skin and in some way their class. That is my major problem. Like you I believe everything in history should be taught. As we teach our children hopefully you learn from your mistakes. And many have been made throughout history as it pertains to how different cultures and races were treated including the white man. Which by the way no one ever talks about. Enclosing I understand your dance and I personally believe that you have a good understanding and personal grasp of the issue. Elementary middle and high schools should be teaching traditional education. Maybe we should talk and think about political science in middle and high schools so we would have a better educated generation coming up when it's time to vote. And I also believe we need to bring back geography as I believe many young people and old have no idea about the subject. I would enjoy a lengthy conversation all about these issues as I am extremely interested in them and believe they play a major major role in development and direction of our children.
-------------
(From school committee candidates Shelly Pereira.)

Hello Gene St Pierre     I just got out of work and saw this post. Iâ€™ll try my best to answer and touch on all the comments. This however is a pretty in-depth question thatâ€™s difficult to answer in a simple Facebook comment. First of all CRT is an academic course load or movement. Itâ€™s not always exactly a class. I have taken some of the derivatives when I was in college. Basically classes that talk about race in relation to social movements and formation of laws. I will say that through my course of study I never felt that it was teaching people to hate white people. And I think that needs to be understood. I certainly do not harbor any white guilt. However with that being said I am NOT in favor of critical race theory or itâ€™s derivatives being taught in our elementary school, middle school or quite frankly high school. I have actually been asked this question several times through my campaign. Iâ€™ve answered it in person as well as on Facebook when people have asked. I was quite surprised that at our forum it wasnâ€™t brought up. There was one question asked by the Fall River reporter wanting to know if we agreed with a school district that terminated a teacher because she did not follow school policy in relation to social media posts. But it didnâ€™t ask us if we thought CRT should be implemented in the classrooms. My reasoning for saying no is that it is an extremely in-depth complicated topic that I do not think children of that age are able to understand or absorb. I think itâ€™s an important topic for those who are choosing to go to school for social work, law-enforcement, legal studies and fields such as that. This has been in the academic arena for as long as I can remember. And I do believe understanding these concepts is helpful in certain professions. I will say that I think teaching truth in history is important. And I donâ€™t think anybody would disagree with that. I think itâ€™s important that all children sitting in our classrooms have their stories told. Which means I am for an ELA class letâ€™s say reading books from men, women people of color etc. I think itâ€™s important that our diverse classrooms have diverse education. ALL children benefit from this. Fall River already has curriculum set forth by the state that implements this. I do wish that teachers had more autonomy in the books letâ€™s say they are choosing. I feel that educators go to school to educate and they should have a more hands on affect on our curriculum.  But that is much different than teaching critical race theory. I have talked to some other candidates, I have not spoke to anybody who wants to implement it but I havenâ€™t spoke to everyone about this. There is a thought by one (truncated)

But when pet for a while she begins tensing up, observing the room more and being more hesitant. She did tolerate pick up towards the end, but waved her feet around and tensed up. Didn't hiss or growl, ate treats after. May need a re-eval in the next few days if she continues to warm up. column36:
ğŸ”¥ğŸ”¥ğŸ”¥TO BE KILLED - 8/28/2021ğŸ”¥ğŸ”¥ğŸ”¥
Please read his storyğŸ‘‡ğŸ‘‡
ğŸ¾ğŸ’”Lived in a crate for most of his lifeğŸ˜¢â€¼ 2 year old Simba is completely at a loss as to what life is all about.  His rescuer then dumped ğŸ˜¡him quickly at a police station where because of an incident, the ACC is portraying him like a bad dog.  HE IS SCARED PUP AT ACCâ€¼ğŸ™and we can conclude that he was also freaked out at the precinct.  He refused the food offered to him, so the officer took the food and walked away, where Simba then bit the policemanâ€™s pant leg.  The temp adopter said thereâ€™s no resource guarding seen in Simba, so what is it?  Scared animals think that humans are out to hurt or do something bad to them.  Imagine an injured cat , how angry and suspicious  he must be, and to approach him is foolish.  Dogs behave the same way when they are badly scared, they are on guard to defend themselves. Thatâ€™s nature. Simba thought the policeman is a threat, he was suspicious and scared, didnâ€™t accept the food, and lashed out when he thought he had the opportunity.  The notes said no provocation, which we humbly say there probably was, but might be perceptible only to the experienced dog person. The crucial point is Simba has not had good experiences with humans.  His adopter said he is a happy excitable puppy, which no one has seen up to this point.  This young boy has not had a life of comfort. In fact his life from the beginning, living in a crate, then 1 week of happiness at home with his adopter,  then betrayal by this very person.  Dumped at the police station then dumped at the ACC.  From the four small walls of his crate, Simba most probably never imagined that his brief taste of freedom and â€œloveâ€ would end this way.  Dogs like Simba need our compassion and understanding, he needs us to help him find the miracle that he needs to get out alive.  We ask you, please help however you can, help this poor puppy who is most likely just over a year old.  He needs a committed experienced home with no children, because he is so scared at the ACC.   Please help Simba, he dies today! 

Simba is fearful & needs an experienced, caring owner and home ASAP. 
 
SIMBA@MANHATTAN ACC

ACC NYC - Brooklyn Center

Medical team writes: Karizma is super stressed and does not really tolerate handling and has lost 4 pounds in the past couple weeks and also did not eat for 5 days in a recent foster home. She does not seem to be eating her food and definitely not her gabapentin either.  Our vets fear that her prolonged anorexia could lead to hepatic lipidosis due to obesity

Our behavior team writes: Karizma is indeed very stressed. She likes to squeeze against the back of the cubby and although she growls, she tolerates very gentle strokes on the body. Our behavior team has tried offering all of our high value food/treats but she is too nervous to eat any of them in their presence. Even if they give her space, she doesnâ€™t show any interest in food.  She may be deteriorating and doesnâ€™t seem to be improving despite the behavior team meeting with her every day.

Thanos
Hello, my name is Thanos. My animal id is #87432. I am a desexed male white dog at the Brooklyn Animal Care Center. The shelter thinks I am about 1 years 3 weeks old.

I came into the shelter as a owner surrender on 2/16/2020, with the surrender reason stated as animal behavior - aggressive towards people.

Sorry, this pet is for new hope partners only.

Thanos it at-risk for behavior reasons. Thanos was originally surrendered at our Queens resource center and transferred to the Brooklyn Care Center in early January because his ownerâ€™s landlord would no longer allow a large-breed dog at the residence due to â€œbreedâ€ restrictions, and because other residents complained about barking when Thanos was left alone. From the onset Thanos exhibited signs of separation anxiety by whining and barking, but responded well when ACC staff sat with him playing soft music. Thanos was adopted by a family with a young child but returned one day later due to some aggression issues that made the child and parents feel uncomfortable. In particular, Thanos would bite at the families feet, often grabbing on to their shoes as they walked by, though never breaking through the shoe to reach skin. While in the shelter Thanos has been difficult to handle and becomes very jumpy and mouthy when handlers attempt to collar and leash him. On 2/26/20 Thanos jumped towards the face of one of his handlers with an open mouth but was thankfully intercepted by a second handler and brought back to his kennel with no incident. Thanos is a big dog weighing in at 70 lbs so when he does jump it can be startling. Allowing Thanos time to decompress and relax in a less stressful environment will better position him for the possibility of permanent placement into a home. This is why we are seeking placement with a New Hope partner. Medically Thanos is healthy.

You may know me from such films as...
https://youtu.be/5Oa_XDwII9I

Let's get to know each other a bit more...
A staff member writes: "I am inevitable." More like "I am adorable and loveable." Thanos is a handsome, sweet boy who is just looking for someone to call his family. He is nothing like Thanos from Avengers, that's for sure. He is all smiles and butt wiggles. Come visit the good and cute version of Thanos today at Staten Island ACC!
