Ron DeSantis has signed a â€˜Parents Bill of Rightsâ€™ that would give Americans more say over schoolsâ€™ education of their children. HB 241 was sent to the governorâ€™s desk on Friday after being passed during the legislative session that ended on April 30. It spells out the rights of parents to â€œdirect the education and care of his or her minor child,â€ which includes the right to â€œaccess and review all school recordsâ€ related to the students. It would also allow for opt-outs regarding any LGBTQ or sex education classes, as well as the right to opt children out of getting certain vaccinations. Those who back the bill see it is a necessary means to check a school system that has gotten increasingly aggressive and politicized. â€œWhat we are seeing is government power is slowly encroaching and expanding. It will do so until the parents assert the rights that they have, but they have to know what those rights are in order to assert them,â€ Senate sponsor Ray Rodrigues, R-Estero, said in April. Critics eager to use the schools push the LGBTQ agenda in the faces of Christian parents slammed the bill, since it â€œcould compel schools to out LGBTQ youth who face unsupportive or dangerous home environments.â€ The schools have become a central battleground for the future of the nation, which is something the radical left has long recognized. Governor Ron DeSantis has been taking executive action to ban Critical Race Theory from being taught in the schools, and has emphasized that the â€œevils of communism and totalitarianism will be taught.â€ DeSantis has also moved to protect biological females from having to compete against biological males who self-identify as girls in school sports. It has become increasingly clear by contrast that Ron DeSantis is one of the few GOP governors willing to fully use his executive authority to ensure that the will of Republican voters is actually represented. LUNA (a precious Sharpei mix ) STROLLS SLOWLY AROUND one of the outside areas at the Manhattan shelter where the volunteers take dogs to get some fresh air, relieve themselves and show them love. For a moment Luna stands there looking lost, hoping to catch a glimpse of something familiar, or just a whiff of something she once knew but there is nothing; nothing that reminds her of home, her family or her favorite stuffie or blanket. Just strangeness and a fear that this may just be the last time. Luna's a cutie with a chunkie frame made for cuddling and slow walks. Someone adored her not that long ago and shared their love and treats with her. At just 4 years old we're hoping Luna will be among the lucky within the next 48 hours and finds a solid, loving BFF or a whole new family to love her enough to keep always keep her safe. The cat was on top of the sibling when approached by the assessor. Anxiously looking around with eyes wide, pupils dilated. Accepted pets but remained unresponsive throughout the interaction. No interest for offered treats nor catnip (sprinkled on the bedding).

The cat tolerates brief attention and petting but may be fearful or stressed in the shelter, and may be intimidated by small children. He may be a little more independent, and may need time to warm up to his new home. The previous owner stated that both cats have been together since kittens for that reason, we recommend that they are adopted as a pair. Due to the behaviors seen in the care center, we feel that this cat will do best in an experienced, adult only home.

ABOUT PLEDGES: Pledges are directly paid to the 501(c)3 NEW HOPE RESCUE PARTNER that pulls the the cat. Pledges do not guarantee a cat's life will be spared but may help a rescue org decide if they can afford to pull the cat and cover his/her vet expenses.

ABOUT US : MLC is 100% volunteer run page. We can help facilitate a rescue, by connecting you with an approved RESCUE group.  We are not affiliated with the NYC ACC.

Medium

Other Notes:
Hussle's owners have cut his nails before, and he went regularly to the vet for this. He will also allow to be bathed. Hussle will become fearful/stressed when being held/restrained. He will bark and lunge at some strangers, particularly men when they approach outside.

Has this dog ever had any medical issues?
No

For a New Family to Know
Hussle was described as a great, very loving dog that loves attention. Hussle's owner said she wishes she had done a better job at socializing him as he will sometimes bark at strangers and growl at other dogs. Hussle is attached to his owners and sleeps in bed with them. He loves to run around, and take walks. Hussle will use the bathroom outdoors and will use the wee wee pad in the home.
Hussle eats dry food in the home- the brand is Nourish Gut Health.
Hussle is crate trained, but he doesn't need the crate anymore. Hussle is a strong chewer and loves kong toys, and plush toys that he can rip up.

Behavior Notes:
Upon intake, Hussle was muzzled and was walked into the shelter by the behavior team. He was not scanned, collared or photographed at the time due to behavior history reported by his owners.

ASSESSMENT NOTES
Hussle came into the care center with a bite history, having bit the owner's boyfriend and the dog sitter on two different occasions. Both bites happen when he was being handle during a stressful situation and neither bites broke skin. Hussle's owner reported that he is uncomfortable while being crowded and will lunge and snap. He also displays his discomfort during walks; growling and lunging at strangers and other dogs. His owner did report that he is social with smaller dogs. In the care center, Hussle can be taken for walks but he remains fearful and avoidant when off leash. He has also escalated to growling, snapping and attempting to bite when he is uncomfortable, for example when he was restrained for his initial medical examination. Hussle requires a very slow approach and gentle coaxing to engage, and will require extensive socialization and further training in a home setting. He will display clear warning signs when he is uncomfortable (growling, choosing to retreat) and he should not be forced into new situations he is not yet comfortable with. Hussle will need an adult-only, experienced foster home through a New Hope Partner.

Do not click the "Adopt Me" button on this webpage. This animal is not directly available for adoption through ACC and is only available by completing the pre-screener form. Adoption inquiries sent directly to ACC will not receive a response.

A Little Bit About Me

Ezra was brought to the Care Center after owner passed away so no information is known about her behavior in the home. However, she have been social and affectionate with staff at ACC. Ezra will lean into handler when being petted and stay near them. Recently, Ezra has begun to deteriorate at the care center, digging in her kennel, ripping the drain covers up. column6: This page posts the cats that are scheduled for euthanasia at the Animal Care Centers of NYC.  We are a volunteer run page, not affiliated with the NYC ACC.  We work hand in hand with registered 501(c)3 Rescues to save animals.
column31: *** SAFE WITH RESCUE! *** â™¦â™¦PRIORITY PLACEMENTâ™¦â™¦ *** A $100 stipend will be offered to the New Hope partner that pulls Beckett 105315. Please note that in order to qualify for the stipend, he cannot go to a boarding facility. *** BROOKLYN ACC ADOPTABLE BECKETT 105315 Zip Code: BROOKLYN NY 11212 Intake Type: Owner Surrender Medical Behavior: 3. Yellow Age: 7 Years (approx) Sex: Male Spayed/Neutered: No Weight: 8.28 DVM Intake Exam Estimated age: 7y Microchip noted on Intake? No History: O/S- hoarding case Subjective: BARH. No csvd Observed Behavior - very nervous, hisses, flees--netted for exam Evidence of Cruelty seen - no Evidence of Trauma seen - no Objective P = wnl R = wnl BCS 5/9 EENT: Eyes clear, ears clean, no nasal or ocular discharge noted Oral Exam: not performed PLN: No enlargements noted H/L: NSR, NMA, CRT < 2, Lungs clear, eupnic ABD: Non painful, no masses palpated U/G: MI with two descended testicles, no discharge MSI: Ambulatory x 4, skin free of parasites, no masses noted, minor abrasions noted on nose and ventral to OD CNS: Mentation appropriate - no signs of neurologic abnormalities Rectal: normal externally Assessment Minor skin abrasions Prognosis: good Plan: no tx needed- should heal on own SURGERY: Okay for surgery 10/18/20 Hiding in cat den upon approach, does not come out when offered treats and does not react when spoken to softly. Nervous after first day, needs some time to adjust. PLEASE CONSIDER SAVING THE LIFE of a NYC ACC Death Row cat with your immediate offer to adopt. TO GET STARTED IMMEDIATELY SEND A PRIVATE MESSAGE TO THIS PAGE (click "Send Message" from our home page). We will respond asap. You will be directed to complete an app with a registered 501(c)3 New Hope Rescue Partner, who is approved to pull cats from the NYC ACC (shelter). We will immediately alert the rescue of your incoming app. ABOUT TRANSPORT: In most cases there is FREE TRANSPORT to your area up to a 4 hr. radius outside of NYC, including all or part of NY, NJ, CT, PA, NH, VT, RI, MA, MD, DE & DC (see the transport map provided). More distant adopters can meet the transport van, (i.e. a NC or VA adopter could meet in MD or DC, or an OH adopter could meet in PA). ABOUT KITTENS: Kittens under 8 wks old & 2 lbs in weight are NOT PUBLICLY ADOPTABLE, due to their fragility. They can only be pulled by a rescue for specially-trained pre-approved kitten foster homes in NY, NJ & CT. Kittens over 8 weeks and 2lbs should preferably go in PAIRS. ABOUT PLEDGES: Pledges are directly paid to the 501(c)3 NEW HOPE RESCUE PARTNER that pulls the the cat. Pledges do not guarantee a cat's life will be spared but may help a rescue org decide if they can afford to pull the cat and cover his/her vet expenses. ABOUT US : MLC is 100% volunteer run page. We can help facilitate a rescue, by connecting you with an approved RESCUE group. We are not affiliated with the NYC ACC.

A Little Bit About Me
Due to the need for extensive behavior modification, this animal is only available for foster/adoption through one of ACC's New Hope Partners.

Only inquiries made through the completed pre-screener will be forwarded to New Hope partners.

Chisholm has arrived into the care centers as a stray, so his home behavior history is unknown. In the care center he has allowed leashing for walks, but has been uncomfortable with direct approach and has not allowed handling. Chisholm has not yet opened up to displaying social behavior toward handlers. He has appeared fearful of stairs and may succeed best in a home without them. Chisholm displayed minimal reaction when introduced to the helper dog and it is unknown how his behavior around dogs may translate into a home. He may succeed best in an adult-only home that will allow him to decompress at his own comfortable pace.

TO BE KILLED 3/12/2020
 
For 7 years, he has lived with his person, slept in the bed, and gone on brisk walks.  Now he is uncomfortable and nervous at the shelter!

Loving and loyal is how his personal described him.  Unfortunately the landlord said that Bully had to go, and so now Bully is scared and alone in an uncertain place.  This is a boy that loves long walks and playing with his kong toy. Housetrained Bully has been kept mostly indoors and will sleep with the owner. He knows his commands, responding to sit, come, down, stay, and go outside. He will go on brisk walks on the leash, pulls very hard, and wanders some but comes back when called when off the leash.  He is a good boy, who had a happy life and now is desperately at risk  Please consider opening your home and your heart to Bully and saving his life!  

Bully ID #81692
Neutered male brown dog 
@ Brooklyn Animal Care Center
About 7 years old
Weight 66lbs
Owner surrender on 3/1/2020, with the surrender reason stated as person circumstance- moving - no pets allowed.

Sorry, this pet is for new hope partners only.

Bully was placed at risk due to behavioral concerns; he was first brought to ACC as a stray by the Police as he was running around on the streets. Bully reunited with his family shortly after. However, a few months later, the Bully's previous owners came to ACC to surrender the dog claiming he needed to surrender due to his new living situation, where dogs were not allowed. There were some concerning behavioral issues reported. Bully bit his previous owner, leaving punctures on his hand. He also bit the officer who was attempting to get him into the crate when he was found running around the first time he was here. The officer stated that no skin was broken. He was also reported to display resources guarding, growling and snapping at those who came close. In the Care Center, we have seen this same type of behavior display by Bully. He is very nervous and aware of his surroundings, and has become difficult to handle due to him displaying fearful aggression. As the days pass by, his behavior is deteriorating and he will benefit from placement as soon as possible. We are recommending placement with an experienced rescue partner who can meet the Bully's needs. Bully is otherwise healthy according to our veterinarian staff.

TO BE KILLED - JULY 29, 2021

:( Surrendered due to family issues, this sweet, shy hunk will steal your heart! Poor Teddy. He's just not use to being treated this way. With no regard, pushed aside, locked in, overlooked, ignored for hours. He's a family boy that enjoyed every single minute he spent with his family, from the adults on down to the children. The time he spent with the kiddos though was the time he enjoyed the most! Teddy adored them. <3 With them, he was playful at the right time but also relaxed when it was time to settle in. He's a gorgeous boy and obviously social and very smart. The ACC has Teddy listed as 2 years old but the owner surrender notes say 6. We're banking on 6 years old with the way Teddy just isnt accepting of what his life has become at the shelter. Personal problems are not our dog's problems. They are ours to straighten up and move on and, no matter how difficult things may seem, hang on to what you've got and that includes the family pet. They have feelings too. Its obvious through Teddy's behavior. He deserves better and we are going to network him for better. Dont stop sharing this sweet, handsome boy until you know he is safe and out of the building and headed to a loving home.

column31: What is â€œWokeness?â€: Understanding â€œCritical Theoryâ€ and The Frankfurt School. Before going any further, we should spend some time defining what â€œwokenessâ€ means. Wokeness is a kind of shorthand for an area of the American political left that is obsessed with identity politics. This is, as the name would imply, the politics of identity. Thus, people are not rational actors, nor are they necessarily economic units. Rather, they are little more than a collection (or, in the parlance of this ideology, the intersections) of skin color and sÃ©xuality. Socioeconomic class might enter into this, but if it does, itâ€™s generally as an afterthought. While Marxism might play some influential role, the wokeists are far more likely to locate the revolutionary subject in, for example, trans-identified black men than it is the working class. One can understand the hostility of the â€œwokeâ€ to the Bernie Sanders campaign in this context: it is much more revolutionary under the guidelines established by wokeism, to put more racial minorities with unusual sÃ©xual identities on the board of Lockheed-Martin and Goldman-Sachs than it is to provide for greater economic equality on behalf of their workers. The bedrock of wokeness is not classical Marxist socialism, but something called â€œcritical theoryâ€ and in particular its variant â€œcritical race theory.â€ This has its roots in the Frankfurt School and an early 20th-century Italian philosopher and politician named Antonio Gramsci. Gramsciâ€™s big idea was that cultural power preceded political power. Thus, to have a Marxist political revolution, one first needed a Marxist cultural revolution. This was to be accomplished by a â€œlong march through the institutions.â€ What this means is that leftists were to infiltrate every institution of significance and gain power within them. We can see the result of this idea today. While American leftists bear little, if any, resemblance to Marxists of old, they have penetrated our institutions and dominate culturally â€“ in academia, in entertainment and increasingly in the economic sphere as well. If one were to read the Communist Manifesto, there are a series of demands at the end, most of which have come to fruition such as universal public education, a progressive income tax, a national bank, and the industrialization of agriculture. This isnâ€™t to say that there is a massive Gramscian conspiracy with thousands of members. Such a thing would be completely impossible to prove or disprove. However, the kernel of the idea has taken root, in part thanks to bona fide promotion in academia, and in part because it simply seems to have largely been a successful operation. Thus â€œcritical theoryâ€ is effectively a sociological philosophy and method that involves constant ideological attacks on Western civilization. Its guiding principle is that Western civilization is based on subjugation, dominance and tyranny. This takes many forms including â€œracism,â€ â€œpatriarchy,â€ â€œheteronormativityâ€ and â€œcissÃ©xismâ€ â€“ all of which are predicated upon weaponized guilt. Weaponized guilt is essentially taking those elements of Western and Anglo-Saxon culture, which prize even-handedness and â€œfair play,â€ and turning them against the culture itself. Indeed, the selection of the name â€œBlack Lives Matterâ€ is a masterstroke in weaponizing guilt: The only possible disagreement (or so say the advocates and allies of the movement) is that you donâ€™t think black lives do actually matter. But, of course, except for extremely isolated, marginalized and numerically insignificant pockets, virtually everyone agrees that all lives have the same value. Indeed, it is a cornerstone of Western civilization and Christian teaching that this is true. It is nearly axiomatic. The Declaration of Independence declares that the basic equality of men is â€œself-evident.â€ No one would even know where to begin â€œarguingâ€ this, simply because it is so accepted as a fact. Itâ€™s worth noting that wokeness largely entered the American political vernacular after the fall of the Occupy Movement. This is not an endorsement of either the Occupy Movement specifically, nor economic reductionism and confiscatory tax redistribution schemes more generally. However, it is worth noting that the corporate affinity for a seemingly â€œradicalâ€ form of politics requiring nothing in the way of actual financial sacrifice began after the death of a political movement demanding corporate accountability and economic redistribution starting at the very top. by Sam Jacobs

PLEASE CONSIDER SAVING THE LIFE of a NYC ACC Death Row cat with your immediate offer to adopt. 

TO GET STARTED IMMEDIATELY SEND A PRIVATE MESSAGE TO THIS PAGE (click "Send Message" from our home page). We will respond asap.  You will be directed to complete an app with a registered 501(c)3 New Hope Rescue Partner,  who is approved to pull cats from the NYC ACC (shelter). We will immediately alert the rescue of your incoming app. 

ABOUT TRANSPORT: In most cases there is FREE TRANSPORT to your area up to a 4 hr. radius outside of NYC, including all or part of NY, NJ, CT, PA, NH, VT, RI, MA, MD, DE & DC (see the transport map provided). More distant adopters can meet the transport van, (i.e. a NC or VA adopter could meet in MD or DC, or an OH adopter could meet  in PA).  

ABOUT KITTENS: Kittens under 8 wks old & 2 lbs in weight are NOT PUBLICLY ADOPTABLE,  due to their fragility.  They can only be pulled by a rescue for specially-trained pre-approved kitten foster homes in NY, NJ & CT.   Kittens over 8 weeks and 2lbs should preferably go in PAIRS.

ABOUT PLEDGES: Pledges are directly paid to the 501(c)3 NEW HOPE RESCUE PARTNER that pulls the the cat. Pledges do not guarantee a cat's life will be spared but may help a rescue org decide if they can afford to pull the cat and cover his/her vet expenses.

ABOUT US : MLC is 100% volunteer run page. We can help facilitate a rescue, by connecting you with an approved RESCUE group.  We are not affiliated with the nyc acc.

column31: History is the story of relationships and the interactions that occur from those relationships. Those stories have multiple versions based on each person's interpretation of what happened. Recognizing there are multiple versions can lead to understanding. With understanding, we can reduce the harm inflicted, wittingly or unwittingly, upon those who have been disenfranchised. Knowing, and understanding, history is vital.
column35: This is a re-share of a post
column36:
June 12, 2021 (Saturday)

Yesterday, David Ignatius had a piece in the Washington Post that uncovered the attempt of the Trump administration to reorder the Middle East along an axis anchored by Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman of Saudia Arabia (more popularly known as MBS),  Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel, and Jared Kushner of the U.S.

To make the deal, the leaders involved apparently wanted to muscle Jordan out of its role as the custodian of Muslim and Christian holy sites in Jerusalem, a role carved out in the 1994 peace treaty between Israel and Jordan that was hammered out under President Bill Clinton. The new dealmakers apparently wanted to scuttle the U.S.-backed accords and replace them with economic deals that would reorder the region.

This story has huge implications for the Middle East, for American government, for religion, for culture, and so on, but something else jumps out to me here: this story is a great illustration of the principles behind Critical Race Theory, which is currently tearing up the Fox News Channel. Together, the attempt to bypass Jordan and the obsession with Critical Race Theory seem to make a larger statement about the current sea change in the U.S. as people increasingly reject the individualist ideology of the Reagan era.

When Kushner set out to construct a Middle East peace plan, he famously told Aaron David Miller, who had negotiated peace agreements with other administrations, that he didnâ€™t want to know about how things had worked in the past. â€œHe said flat out, donâ€™t talk to me about history,â€ Miller told Chris McGreal of The Guardian, â€œHe said, I told the Israelis and the Palestinians not to talk to me about history too.â€

Kushner apparently thought he could create a brand new Middle East with a brand new set of alliances that would begin with changing long standing geopolitics in Jerusalem, the city three major world religions consider holy. It is eye-popping to imagine what would have happened if we had torn up decades of agreements and tried to graft onto a troubled area an entirely new way of interacting, based not on treaties but on the interests of this new axis. Apparently, the hope was that throwing enough money at the region would have made the change palatable. But most experts think that weakening Jordan, long a key U.S. ally in the region, and removing its oversight of the holy sites, would have ushered in violence.

The heart of the American contribution to the idea of reworking the Middle East along a new axis with contracts, rather than treaties, seems to have been that enough will and enough money can create new realities.

The idea that will and money could create success was at the heart of the Reagan Revolution. Its adherents championed the idea that any individual could prosper in America, so long as the government stayed out of his (it was almost always his) business.

Critical Race Theory challenges this individualist ideology. CRT emerged in the late 1970s in legal scholarship written by people who recognized that legal protections for individuals did not, in fact, level the playing field in America. They noted that racial biases are embedded in our legal system. From that, other scholars noted that racial, ethnic, gender, class, and other biases are embedded in the other systems that make up our society. 

Historians began to cover this ground long ago. Oklahoma historian Angie Debo established such biases in the construction of American law in her book, â€œAnd Still the Waters Run: The Betrayal of the Five Civilized Tribesâ€ back in 1940. Since then, historians have explored the biases in our housing policies, policing, medical care, and so on, and there are very few who would suggest that our systems are truly neutral. 

So why is Critical Race Theory such a flashpoint in todayâ€™s political world? Perhaps in part because it rejects the Republican insistence that an individual can create a prosperous life by will alone. It says that, no matter how talented someone might be, or how eager and dedicated, they cannot always contend against the societal forces stacked against them. It argues for the important weight of systems, established through time, rather than the idea that anyone can create a new reality.

It acknowledges the importance of history.

column6: Presumed Incompetent is a pathbreaking account of the intersecting roles of race, gender, and class in the working lives of women faculty of color.
column31: â€œCritics suggest that anti-racist teaching is dogmatic, unpatriotic, and an impediment to critical thinking. They have, in recent weeks, irresponsibly clumped together anti-racist teaching, critical race theory, ethnic studies, and anything else involving the systematic study of race and racism, painting them as one heap of race-talk mumbo jumbo. Lost in the discourse on both sides, however, is the acknowledgment that Black teachers, as early as the 19th century, have been deeply engaged in the work of challenging racial domination in American schools. The traditions of African American teachers provide the country with a model, a vital intellectual resource for more nuanced conversations about the place and possibility of anti-racism in the classroom.â€ ~Jarvis Givens

column36:
August 28, 2021 (Saturday)

Today, Americans across the country marched for voting rights.

They recognize that our right to have a say in our government is slipping out of our hands. At a rally in Washington, Martin Luther King III told the crowd, â€œOur country is backsliding to the unconscionable days of Jim Crow. And some of our senators are saying, â€˜Well, we canâ€™t overcome the filibuster,â€™.... I say to you today: Get rid of the filibuster. That is a monument to white supremacy we must tear down.â€

Since 1986, Republicans have worked to limit access to the polls, recognizing that when more people vote, they lose. Those restrictions took off after 2013 when, in the Shelby County v. Holder decision, the Supreme Court gutted the provision of the 1965 Voting Rights Act that required the Department of Justice to sign off on changes to voting in states with histories of racial discrimination. 

That decision opened the way to voter restrictions, but voting laws have come especially fast and furious this year. Republicans have refused to accept that the election of Democrat Joe Biden was legitimate and, in Republican-dominated states, have worked to make sure Democrats do not have the power to elect another president in the future. Between January 1 and July 14 of this year, at least 18 states have enacted 30 laws restricting access to the vote.

Their plan is clearly to make sure those states stay Republican, no matter what the voters actually want. 

This lack of competition destroys Democratsâ€™ chances of winning elections, but it also pushes the Republican Party further and further to the right. With states sewn up for a Republican victory, potential Republican presidential candidates have to worry less about winning a general election than about winning the primaries. 

Because primary voters are always the most energized and partisan voters, and because for the Republicans that currently means staunch Trump supporters, those vying to be Republican front runners are the Trump extremists: Florida Governor Ron DeSantis, for example, and even Floridaâ€™s Matt Gaetz and Georgiaâ€™s Marjorie Taylor Greene, who recently have been touring the early voting states of Iowa and New Hampshire attacking mask requirements and vaccine mandates, critical race theory and the infrastructure bills currently under discussion in Congress.  

Vote-rigging in Republican-dominated states leads logically to a Republican extremist winning the White House in 2024. 

Congress has before it two voting rights bills that would help to restore a level playing field between the two parties. One, the For the People Act, protects the right to vote, ends partisan gerrymandering, limits corporate money in elections, and requires new ethics rules for elected officials. The House passed the For the People Act in March.

On Tuesday, August 24, the House passed the second of the two voting rights bills, the John Lewis Voting Rights Advancement Act of 2021, also known as H.R. 4, which expands the system of preclearance that had been in the 1965 Voting Rights Act before 2013. Under the John Lewis bill, the Department of Justice has to sign off on voting changes not simply in states with a longstanding history of discrimination, but also in states anywhere in the country that have shown a pattern of violations of voting rights.

Both of these measures are stalled in the Senate, where Republicans, who insist that states, not the federal government, must have the final say in who gets to vote, have vowed to filibuster them. Unless the Democrats can agree to carve out an exception to the filibuster for voting rights, the measures will die. 

And today, Americans across the country marched for voting rights. 

Today is the 58th anniversary of the 1963 March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom. It was on this day in 1963 that the Reverend Martin Luther King, Jr., gave his â€œI Have a Dreamâ€ speech. 

Dr. King anchored the speeches for the day, though: before him spoke the chair of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee, a young John Lewis. Just 23 years old, he had been one of the thirteen original Freedom Riders, white and black students traveling together from Washington, D.C., to New Orleans to challenge segregation. â€œIt was very violent. I thought I was going to die. I was left lying at the Greyhound bus station in Montgomery unconscious,â€ Lewis later recalled.

Two years later, as Lewis and 600 marchers hoping to register African American voters in Alabama stopped to pray at the end of the Edmund Pettus Bridge in Selma, mounted police troopers charged the marchers, beating them with clubs and bullwhips. They fractured Lewisâ€™s skull.

The attack in Selma created momentum for voting rights. Just after the attack, President Lyndon Baines Johnson called for Congress to pass a national voting rights bill. It did. On August 6, 1965, Johnson signed the Voting Rights Act authorizing federal supervision of voter registration in districts where (truncated)

6-Jun-2020 Progress Exam
Vet Notes: 2:27 PM

Hx:
Stray intake SIACC-reported to have been covered in fleas, ticks, and lice per finder. Wound noted on intake and transferred to BACC for further diagnostics.*Given revolution on intake* FAD, underweight, LFL lameness with marked swelling appreciated. Started on clavamox, simbadol, and onsior.
Today, 6/6-Progress exam, overall recheck and scheduled for in house bloodwork and radiographs

SO: BARH, no c/s/v/d. Excellent appetite. Urine noted in litter box, no stool. Very sweet and affectionate, at front of kennel seeking attention, leaning into pets, purring, and making biscuits. Allowed all handling.

P = WNL
R = WNL
BCS = 3/9

PLN: No enlargements noted
H/L: No murmurs or arrhythmias ausculted. Lungs clear, eupnic, no crackles or wheezes.
ABD: Soft, non-painful, no masses palpated
U/G: MI, 2 palpable testicles, no discharge
MSI: Ambulatory x 4 with weight bearing lameness appreciated on LFL, no fractures palpated, moderate to severe soft tissue swelling appreciated from elbow to carpus with moderate errythema, uncomfortable on palpation, difficult to fully extend under sedation. Small wound (dried scab) noted on lateral aspect of antebrachium. Generalized thinning of fur noted on ventrum and hindlimbs (consistent with FAD) with severe lice infestation. Post shave dry and flaky skin, pressure sores noted on hocks, mild dermatitis appreciated on ventrum, no masses noted. 3-4 ticks noted in axillary region and hindlimbs.
CNS: Mentation appropriate - no signs of neurologic abnormalities
Rectal: Not performed, externally normal
Wood's Lamp Exam: Negative

Assessment:
Ticks-treated 6/5
Lice-treated 6/5
FAD
Underweight
LFL lameness/swelling r/o cellulitis
Wound
Tail fracture

Prognosis:
Fair-Good

Plan:
CTM while at BACC
Keep in medical
Sedated with Telazol 0.04ml IM once. Shaved majority of coat and removed as many lice as possible. Clipped and cleaned LFL no draining tracts or further wounds noted. Extended original wound (small scab) and no discharge appreciated. Cleaned with chlorhexadine and closed with skin glue.
LFL radiographs revealed marked soft tissue swelling with no evidence of a fracture. Abdominal radiographs revealed large amount of ingesta and gas in GIT with no evidence of FB/obstruction. Tail fracture noted. Open physis appreciated on radiographs-suspect P is close to 1yr
Continue Clavamox 13.75mg/kg PO BID x 10 days until 6/15
Continue Simbadol 0.24mg/kg SQ SID x 5 days until 6/9
Continue Onsior 2mg/kg SQ SID x 3 days until 6/8
Monitor closely on daily rounds, repeat Revolution in 2 weeks (6/19) for a total of 3 treatments

BASIC INFORMATION: 
Carlos previously stayed with a dog and a cat and 1 adult. The caller said, the dog is good, but it chewed the door and the sofa. He may have separation anxiety. He it a sweet dog, was great to me (Kat). Carlo's behavior around children is unknown. The caller had a dog and Carlos was good with the dog. Carlos was also good with the cat, as per caller. He has no known bite history. 

PLAYGROUP NOTES - DOG TO DOG SUMMARIES: Carlos's finder reported that he did not display any concerning behavior when interacting with the resident dog. When off leash at the Care Center, Carlos keeps to himself as he wanders in a group of small male and female dogs. He growls at the other small dogs when they sniff his rear of greet him face to face.

Recommendations:
No young children (under 5)
Single Pet Home 
Recommend no dog parks
Recommendations comments:
Recommend No dog Parks: Due to Carlos's uncomfortable behavior during playgroup (see DOG-DOG SUMMARY) the Behavior Department recommends that Carlos not be taken to dog parks. Reward-based, force-free training can be utilized to counter-condition and desensitize Carlos to help him associate other dogs with positive experiences, such as toys or treats.

Adoption Summary:
Carlos would do best in a home with an experienced adopter who is familiar with his breed. He would love to be your one and only and should not go to a home with other pets or young children. 
He's a friendly fella but takes some time to warm up to new people. He has some dental needs that will be the adopter's responsibility.

column36:
Gumbo has been placed with a NH rescue 

A private donor has graciously offered to pay $500 to the New Hope partner that pulls Gumbo Additionally this private donor has offered to assist with transportation!

OUR HEARTS ARE BREAKING FOR POOR GUMBO!  We do not know what happened that he ended up at the shelter, but it is certainly not where he imagined himself at 7 years old.  And he is struggling with it!  That is no surprise; this poor dear.  He is all alone and afraid now and is running out of reason to hope!  To make matters even worse for Gumbo, we have no background or notes on him that tell good stories of how he was in his prior home!  He has nothing but his behavior at the shelter to help save his life!  So please PLEASE see past all this reactive fear and know that there is a sweet boy behind all the bluster!  Please SHARE pledge FOSTER adopt and save Gumbo's life!

GUMBO, ID# #124289, 7 yrs old, 72 lbs, male
Brooklyn ACC, Large Mixed Breed,
Surrender Reason: stray
Shelter Assessment Rating: NEW HOPE ONLY
No children (under 13)
Medical Behavior Rating: 3. Yellow

Gumbo is on the emergency placement list due to behavioral reasons. Gumbo has been observed to growl, lunge and hard bark in kennel; he is unable to be safely handled. Medically, Gumbo has dental disease and dermatitis.

INTAKE DATE: 8/18/2021

BEHAVIOR NOTES
Date of assessment:: 8/22/2021

Summary:: Gumbo appeared fearful and highly stressed upon arriving into care center. He did not display social behavior and appeared uncomfortable with direct handling and approach. Since arrival, Gumbo has been observed to lunge, growl, and hard bark in his kennel, charging forward when handlers approach. He has not been receptive to treats or slow approach. Due to Gumbo's observed behavior and inability to safely handle him, we believe that he is not a safe candidate to be placed back into the public.

BEHAVIOR DETERMINATION:: New Hope Only

Recommendations:: No children (under 13),Place with a New Hope partner

Recommendations comments:: No children: Due to the high level of fear and potential for defensive aggression seen at the care center, we recommend an adult only home.

Place with a New Hope partner: Due to the high level of fear and potential for defensive aggression seen at the care center, we recommend placement with a New Hope partner who can provide any necessary behavior modification (force-free, positive reinforcement-based) and re-evaluate behavior in a stable home environment before placement into a permanent home.

Potential challenges: : Fearful/potential for defensive aggression

Potential challenges comments:: Fearful/potential for defensive aggression: Gumbo is highly fearful at the care center, running forward and growling loudly when people approach his kennel. Due to this behavior, he has been unable to be handled at the care center. He will need a very slow approach and positive reinforcement behavior modification. Please see handout on Fearful/potential for defensive aggression.

MEDICAL ASSESSMENT

8/21/2021

Unable to administer second dose of trazodone within 24 hours.
